"André J.-C., Royer J.-F.","Short-term climatic fluctuations and the interpretation of recent observations in terms of greenhouse effect [Les fluctuations a court terme du climat et l'interpretation des observations recentes en terme d'effet de serre]",1999,"Comptes Rendus de l'Academie de Sciences - Serie IIa: Sciences de la Terre et des Planetes","328","4",,"261","272",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032999706&partnerID=40&md5=fce7abb0a0a6c6954c5dadc13329cbd3","Ctr. Europ. Rech. Form. Avancee C., 31057 Toulouse Cedex 1, France; Météo-France, Ctr. Natl. de Rech. Meteorologiques, 31057 Toulouse Cedex 1, France","André, J.-C., Ctr. Europ. Rech. Form. Avancee C., 31057 Toulouse Cedex 1, France; Royer, J.-F., Météo-France, Ctr. Natl. de Rech. Meteorologiques, 31057 Toulouse Cedex 1, France","Simulations of future climate made with coupled general circulation models of the atmosphere and ocean predict that the increase of the concentration of greenhouse gases released in the atmosphere by man's activities will have a large influence on the climate of the next century. The identification of the climatic impact produced by the rapid increase in carbon dioxide concentration in the last decades is made difficult by strong interannual climate variability, and requires the application of statistical techniques combining several climatic indicators (method of climatic 'fingerprints') so as to improve the detection of a possible anthropogenic perturbation. In this paper we review the evolution through the last decades of several climate indicators showing global warming, its geographical distribution, sea level, the hydrological cycle and the response of vegetation, and we compare them to the model results predicted in climate scenarios. The coherence between model results and observed climatic trends shows that the additional greenhouse effect is starting to become detectable in recent climatic data.","Climate change; Greenhouse effect; Numerical simulations; Statistical methods","climate change; greenhouse effect",,,,,,"Allen Jr., L.H., Baker, J.T., Boote, K.J., The CO 2 fertilization effect: Higher carbohydrate production and retention as biomass and seed yield (1996) Global Climate Change and Agricultural Production, pp. 65-100. , Bazzaz F. et Sombroek W. (éds), John Wiley & Sons, New York; Barthelet, P., Bony, S., Braconnot, P., Braun, A., Cariolle, D., Cohensolal, E., Dufresne, J.-L., Valcke, S., Global coupled simulations of climate change due to increased atmospheric CO 2 concentration (1998) C. R. Acad. Sci. Paris, 326, pp. 677-684. , série lla; Basist, A.N., Chelliah, M., Comparison of tropospheric temperatures derived from the INCEP/NCAR reanalysis, NCEP operational analysis, and the Microwave Sounding Unit (1997) Bull. Amer. Meteorol. Soc., 78, pp. 1431-1447; Battisti, D.S., Sarachik, E.S., Understanding and predicting ENSO (1995) Rev. Geophys., 33, pp. 1367-1376; Becker, M., Bert, C.D., Bouchon, J., Dupouet, J.-L., Picard, J.-F., Ulrich, E., Long-term changes in forest productivity in northeastern France: The dendroecological approach (1995) Forest Decline and Atmospheric Deposition Effects in the French Mountains, pp. 143-156. , Landmann G. et Bonneau M. (éds), Springer-Verlag, Berlin, Heidelberg, New York; Berger, A., Milankovitch theory and climate (1988) Rev. Geophys., 26, pp. 624-657; Carnell, R.E., Senior, C.A., Changes in mid latitude variability due to increasing greenhouse gases and sulphate aerosols (1998) Climate Dynam., 14, pp. 369-383; Casella, E., Soussana, J.-F., Loiseau, P., Long-term effects of CO 2 enrichment and temperature increase on a temperate grass sward. I. Productivity and water use (1996) Plant and Soil, 182, pp. 83-99; Cazenave, A., Dominh, K., Gennero, M.C., Ferret, B., Global mean sea level changes observed by Topex-Poseidon and ERS-1 (1998) Phys. Chem. Earth, , sous presse; Chahine, M.T., The hydrological cycle and its influence on climate (1992) Nature, 359, pp. 373-380;